	<tr>
		
			<td colspan="2" bgcolor="#DEDACB" background="http://www.everlore.com/gimages/tb_beige.gif">
		
				<font face="verdana" size="2" color="black">
				These are the thoughts and observations from Insin the 16 lvl mage. First let me talk about the main advantage of our class. First and foremost being able to conj. things. (Pets water food bandages etc.) You are the provisioner of your group. You bring the ability of summoning all things needed for combat from water food to later levels arrows and very good weapons. I'm using a summoned dagger from a high lvl mage that does 5 dmg with a 20 delay. I was using a crysknife not bad in itself but is no match to my conj. one. I want to end a myth right now. As a mage you also bring to the group an excellent tank. My lvl 16 earth pet can solo the lower lvl of Black Burrow with ease. Its nice to gain faction while I sit back and meditate. :) A mage also has some very respectable DD and AE spells can do some very good damage with my spells. Never think that as a mage you could out damage a wizard. They cast very fast. A wizard friend and I tested this one night. He could cast 4 spells to my 3 in the same time. At later levels that could be a difference of hundreds of hp's worth of damage to the MOB. As we all know there is balance with all char. My wizard friend has no pet to tank for him so the MOB goes after him first when he drops the big nuke on him. I send in my pet and sit back and cast. My pet and I can easily solo white /black MOBS.  There are many types of strategies to using a pet. As the pet gets stronger from lvl to lvl these change somewhat. Here are a few of my tips for using pets 1st. Make your pet buttons. 2nd buff your pet as much as you can. Ask others in your group to buff it too. I&#8217;ll give you an example of this. My group and I were sitting in west commons waiting for the ghouls to spawn when a kodiak walked by. I always brag on my pet about how strong he is and how he could solo almost any MOB in the zone. My group said  prove it and send it after the kodiak.  I agreed if they would fully buff the pet up .I conned the kodiak dark blue to me at 15. The kodiak is easily lvl 16 to 17 range. Tough challenge for a lvl 12 earth pet. But the pet was looking brave and buffed to the hilt. I sent it in to meet the huge kodiak in battle. The battle seemed doomed from the start. This kodaik was tough. I kept a close eye on the pet&#8217;s health as it steadily went down. Watching the battle as it scrolled across my text box. I noticed that the pet was hitting for 20 bashing for 10 and casting in 1 round Very tough for a pet. The battle was long and terse with many swings of momentum. If this were a movie my pet the mighty hero would have been victorious. But like in real life the true champion usually is victorious. Death came with honor for Jerbek. I walked up to the Kodiak, and with one pierce of my blade the kodiak fell to the ground. I didn't win the bet but my friends were very impressed with the strength of the pet. The moral of this story is your pets at whatever lvl can benefit from buffs and heals and can fight way above its lvl. 3rd let the pet tank for a bit before you start to nuke the MOB with your spells. Make sure the MOB is very mad at the pet and it will completely ignore you as cast on it from behind. <BR>
Lets talk about Soloing a mage. You have all your buttons made so you can have your pet attack, back off and report its health. You&#8217;re in your favorite hunting area and you  /con a Mob and find its white/black. An even fight for you but not when you have your pet too. First does the MOB poison, or cause any other type of damage over time? This can cause you major problems. It weakens the pet and will most likely kill it in a short amount of time. So send in the pet and let the MOB get really mad at the pet (it takes about 15 sec&#8217;s) then you sit and nuke it to death. Always keep an eye on your pet&#8217;s health. If it looks close to death, stand in and pierce for a couple of rounds to distract the MOB from your pet. When the MOB hits you for a couple of bubbles of health step back and cast again. This will give your pet a chance to regenerate some hp's and will last longer in the fight. When you kill the MOB you should be close to out of mana and your pet should be close to death but you have felled a Mob above you in lvl. Congratulations. Here is the frustrating part of playing a caster. Meditating. You will spend a lot of time looking at your spell book.  <BR>
<BR>
Now lets get to the area of armor and weapons. When choosing armor pay AC no mind. Does it increase your stats? ( Int. Wis. Dex. Hp's  Mana)  That should be your main focus. Weapons are up to you. How do want to RP your character. Will you be a sneaky mage and back stab with a dagger?  Or will you beat the MOB with a staff? Eventually at high lvl&#8217;s weapons won't matter.          At lvl 16 I have about 300 hps that&#8217;s 10 hits from a Kodiak. I'm not going to stand in and try to pierce it for 10- 18 dmg. Save your money and buy a weapon that casts an effect. Remember you are not a tank [that is what the smelly barbarians are for ;) ] stand back away from the battle and cast. <BR>
I'm not a believer in telling a new char where and what to hunt. After lvl 4 there are many places in the areas around Queens and Freeport to find Mobs in your lvl. I will leave you with just a few things to make you experiences in Norath more enjoyable. Have a plan before battle. Always buff your pet before battle (fire shield, burnout, etc.). Trade your conj. provisions for buffs and SOW's.  Treat the people you find in your travels with respect.  Don't kill steal on purpose.  May your loots be bountiful and your journeys swift.<BR>

				</font>
			</td>

	</tr>
	
